05008nam a22005895i 9780822383697DE-B159720201212080620.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||201212t20022003ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223836977 a10.1515/97808223836972doi  a(DE-B1597)553675  a(OCoLC)245538644  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aHN310.A5bR64 2002 7aHIS0330002bisacsh04a986.1/2606322211 aRoldán, Mary, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBlood and Fire :bLa Violencia in Antioquia, Colombia, 1946-1953 /cMary Roldán; Irene Silverblatt, Sonia Saldívar-Hull, Walter D. Mignolo. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2002] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (416 p.) :b14 tables, 18 figures, 6 b&w photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLatin America otherwise : languages, empires, nations00tFrontmatter -- tAbout the Series -- tAbout the Photographs -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Medellín and Core Municipalities -- t2. Bajo Cauca, Magdalena Medio, and the Northeast -- t3. Urabá and Western Antioquia -- t4. Urrao and the Southwest -- tEpilogue -- tAppendix A: Tables -- tAppendix B: Maps -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBetween 1946 and 1966a surge of violence in Colombia left 200,000 dead in one of the worst conflicts the western hemisphere has ever experienced. the first seven years of this little-studied period of terror, known as la Violencia, is the subject of Blood and Fire. Scholars have traditionally assumed that partisan politics drove La Violencia, but Mary Roldán challenges earlier assessments by providing a nuanced account of the political and cultural motives behind the fratricide. Although the author acknowledges that partisan animosities played an important role in the disintegration of peaceful discourse into violence, she argues that conventional political conflicts were intensified by other concerns.Through an analysis of the evolution of violence in Antioquia, which at the time was the wealthiest and most economically diverse region of Colombia, Roldán demonstrates how tensions between regional politicians and the weak central state, diverse forms of social prejudice, and processes of economic development combined to make violence a preferred mode of political action. Privatization of state violence into paramilitary units and the emergence of armed resistance movements exacted a horrible cost on Colombian civic life, and these processes continue to plague the country.Roldan's reading of the historical events suggests that Antioquia's experience of la Violencia was the culmination of a brand of internal colonialism in which regional identity formation based on assumptions of cultural superiority was used to justify violence against racial or ethnic "others" and as a pretext to seize land and natural resources. Blood and Fire demonstrates that, far from being a peculiarity of the Colombians, la Violencia was a logical product of capitalist development and state formation in the modern world.This is the first study to analyze intersections of ethnicity, geography, and class to explore the genesis of Colombian violence, and it has implications for the study of repression in many other nations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 0aPolitical violencezColombiazAntioquia (Department)xHistory. 0aViolencezColombiazAntioquia (Department). 7aHISTORY / Latin America / South America.2bisacsh1 aMignolo, Walter D., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSaldívar-Hull, Sonia, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSilverblatt, Irene, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of